Mechanistic Validation of the Vagal Brake: A Mathematical Architecture for Cardiac–Neural Coupling and Executive Function

Author: ouadi Maakoul 

---

Abstract

The Neurovisceral Integration Model posits that heart rate variability (HRV), particularly high‑frequency vagal tone, reflects the capacity for prefrontal cortical regulation of emotional and cognitive processes. The hypothesized “vagal brake”—a phasic inhibition of the amygdala by the ventromedial prefrontal cortex (vmPFC) mediated by the vagus nerve—remains largely untested at the level of causal, non‑linear dynamics. This dissertation develops a comprehensive mathematical and computational architecture to quantify the causal influence of cardiac resonance (0.1 Hz respiratory‑cardiac entrainment) on prefrontal oxygenation and executive performance. By integrating advanced time‑frequency analysis (continuous wavelet transform, cross‑wavelet coherence), non‑linear causality measures (Convergent Cross Mapping), and biomarker kinetics (salivary alpha‑amylase and cortisol), we propose a unified framework to test whether the 0.1 Hz resonance state drives a measurable “vagal brake index.” No physical experiments are conducted; instead, we present the theoretical underpinnings, signal processing pipelines, and mathematical proofs that establish the feasibility and rigor of such an investigation. The proposed architecture provides a replicable, open‑science blueprint for future experimental studies and offers novel computational biomarkers for clinical and high‑performance applications.

---

1. Introduction

1.1 Problem Statement

Heart‑brain interactions have long been recognized in psychophysiology, yet the precise causal pathways remain elusive. Commercial biofeedback devices claim that “heart coherence” improves cognitive performance, but the underlying neural and autonomic mechanisms are not rigorously validated. The central question is whether the 0.1 Hz resonance frequency—the frequency at which the baroreflex and respiration naturally entrain—causally enhances prefrontal executive function by engaging the vagal brake.

1.2 Objectives

1. To develop a mathematical framework for quantifying the phase‑locking and causal direction between HRV (specifically power in the 0.1 Hz band) and prefrontal cortical oxygenation measured by functional near‑infrared spectroscopy (fNIRS).
2. To model the mediating role of sympathetic arousal (salivary alpha‑amylase, sAA) and HPA‑axis activation (salivary cortisol) in the relationship between cardiac resonance and executive performance.
3. To propose a composite metric—the Vagal Brake Index (VBI)—that integrates spectral, causal, and endocrine information as a theoretical signature of top‑down regulation.

1.3 Significance

This work provides a rigorous computational foundation for future experimental studies. It bridges non‑linear dynamical systems theory, biomedical signal processing, and psychoneuroendocrinology, offering a testable architecture for one of the most compelling models in affective neuroscience.

