2. Theoretical Framework

2.1 Neurovisceral Integration Model (Thayer & Lane, 2000)

The model posits that the vagus nerve serves as a structural and functional link between the heart and the prefrontal cortex. High vagal tone, indexed by HRV, reflects the integrity of a central autonomic network (CAN) that includes the vmPFC, anterior cingulate cortex, amygdala, and brainstem. This network enables flexible emotional and cognitive responding.

2.2 Polyvagal Theory (Porges, 2007)

Porges’ theory emphasizes the myelinated vagus as a “vagal brake” that can rapidly inhibit sympathetic outflow, thereby promoting calm, focused states. The theory predicts that voluntary control of breathing at the resonant frequency (0.1 Hz) optimizes this vagal influence.

2.3 The Vagal Brake Hypothesis

We formalize the vagal brake as a directed causal influence from cardiac rhythm to prefrontal cortical activity. Specifically, when the heart is entrained at 0.1 Hz, the baroreflex generates a rhythmic afferent signal that reaches the nucleus tractus solitarius (NTS) and, via projections to the prefrontal cortex, modulates excitability and metabolic demand. This leads to reduced “interference” from limbic regions during cognitively demanding tasks.

