4. Proposed Architecture

We design a computational pipeline that simulates the processing of multi‑modal signals (ECG, fNIRS, sAA, cortisol) as they would be acquired in a crossover experiment. The architecture consists of four modules:

4.1 Data Acquisition Module (Simulated)

· ECG: 3‑lead, 500 Hz, with simulated R‑peak timings based on a dynamical model of heart rate at 0.1 Hz resonance.
· fNIRS: 16 channels over prefrontal cortex, generating synthetic \Delta[\text{HbO}] signals that include a 0.1 Hz component when coupled to the cardiac input.
· Salivary samples: Time‑stamped at baseline, post‑stress, and recovery periods; concentrations modeled by exponential rise and decay functions.

4.2 Preprocessing Module

· R‑peak detection (Pan‑Tompkins) and cubic spline interpolation to 4 Hz.
· fNIRS: wavelet‑based motion correction, band‑pass filtering.
· Artifact rejection: threshold‑based exclusion of epochs with excessive movement or signal saturation.

4.3 Fusion & Causality Module

· Compute wavelet coherence (WTC) for each subject, extracting mean coherence in the 0.1 Hz band during induction and task.
· Perform CCM: determine embedding dimension E using false‑nearest neighbors; compute cross‑map skill \rho for both directions (HRV→fNIRS and fNIRS→HRV); test convergence with increasing library length.
· Calculate the Vagal Brake Index:

VBI = \frac{\overline{P_{HRV}(0.1\,\text{Hz})}}{\overline{P_{fNIRS}(0.1\,\text{Hz})}} \cdot \Phi,

where \overline{P} denotes average power in the 0.1 Hz band during the induction phase, and \Phi is the mean phase‑locking value (PLV) at that frequency.

4.4 Biomarker Integration Module

· Compute AUCg and AUCi for sAA and cortisol from the simulated time points.
· Use SEM to test whether condition (0.1 Hz vs. 0.2 Hz) affects executive performance (MSIT interference cost) directly and indirectly through changes in VBI and AUCi (sAA/cortisol).

