5. Mathematical Proofs

We provide theoretical arguments that the proposed metrics can, under ideal conditions, detect the vagal brake.

5.1 Proof of Phase‑Locking at Resonance

Theorem 1 (Coherence Peak).
If the heart is entrained at 0.1 Hz via resonant breathing, and if the vagal brake hypothesis holds, then the wavelet coherence R_n^2(s_{0.1}) will be significantly greater than the coherence at neighboring scales, and the phase difference will be stable (low circular variance).

Sketch: The baroreflex generates a 0.1 Hz oscillation in HRV. This afferent signal projects to the NTS and then to the prefrontal cortex via the parabrachial nucleus and thalamus. If the cortex’s hemodynamic response follows the neural activity, the fNIRS signal will exhibit a 0.1 Hz component that is phase‑locked to the HRV signal. Wavelet coherence captures this localized synchronization.

5.2 Proof of Directed Causality

Theorem 2 (Convergence).
If the heart drives prefrontal activity, then CCM will show convergence (increasing cross‑map skill with library length) for H \rightarrow B but not for B \rightarrow H. If the relationship is bidirectional, both directions may converge, but the asymmetry in cross‑map skill (or the rate of convergence) will indicate the dominant direction.

Sketch: CCM relies on Takens’ theorem, which states that the shadow manifold of a univariate time series is diffeomorphic to the original system’s attractor. If H influences B, then the state of H is embedded in the history of B; thus, cross‑mapping from B to H improves with more data. The converse may not hold if B does not drive H.

5.3 Proof of Mediation

Theorem 3 (Indirect Effect).
In the proposed mediation model, if (a) condition affects VBI and/or AUCi, and (b) VBI and/or AUCi predict performance while controlling for condition, then the indirect effect is non‑zero, indicating that the effect of resonance on performance is partially mediated by the vagal brake and sympathetic recovery.

Sketch: This follows from standard mediation theory (Baron & Kenny, 1986). Bootstrapping provides non‑parametric confidence intervals, avoiding the assumption of normality of the product term.

