Appendix C: System Architecture and Design

C.1 Overview of Computational Pipeline

The pipeline processes simulated or real multi‑modal data to compute the Vagal Brake Index and perform mediation analysis. It consists of four main modules:

1. Data Acquisition Module – Simulates or loads ECG, fNIRS, and salivary biomarker data.
2. Preprocessing Module – Cleans signals, detects R‑peaks, resamples, filters, and computes derived signals (HRV time series, oxy‑Hb).
3. Fusion & Causality Module – Computes wavelet coherence, CCM, and the Vagal Brake Index.
4. Biomarker Integration Module – Calculates AUC for biomarkers and runs mediation analysis.

All modules are designed to be modular, with clearly defined interfaces to allow swapping of simulation vs. real data.

C.2 Module Specifications

C.2.1 Data Acquisition Module

· Input: Configuration parameters (e.g., subject ID, condition, session type).
· Output: Raw ECG (500 Hz), raw fNIRS (multiple channels, 10 Hz), timestamps for salivary samples.
· Simulation: For the theoretical architecture, we generate synthetic data using known dynamical models (e.g., a van der Pol oscillator for HRV at 0.1 Hz, a hemodynamic response model for fNIRS with added 0.1 Hz component when coupling is active).

C.2.2 Preprocessing Module

· ECG:
  · R‑peak detection via Pan‑Tompkins algorithm.
  · RR interval extraction, outlier removal (interpolation for >20% deviation).
  · Cubic spline interpolation to 4 Hz → HRV time series.
· fNIRS:
  · Convert raw intensities to optical density changes.
  · Apply MBLL to compute \Delta[\text{HbO}] and \Delta[\text{HbR}].
  · Band‑pass filter (0.01–0.5 Hz) using a zero‑phase Butterworth filter.
  · Motion artifact removal using wavelet‑based method.
· Salivary biomarkers:
  · Load concentration values at specified times.
  · Compute AUCg and AUCi using trapezoidal integration.

C.2.3 Fusion & Causality Module

· Wavelet Coherence:
  · Use Morlet wavelet with scales corresponding to 0.5–0.01 Hz.
  · Compute wavelet coherence between HRV and fNIRS oxy‑Hb.
  · Extract mean coherence in the 0.1 Hz band during induction and task phases.
  · Compute phase‑locking value (PLV) as  \frac{1}{N} \left| \sum e^{i\Delta\phi(t)} \right| .
· Convergent Cross Mapping:
  · Determine embedding dimension  E  via false‑nearest neighbors.
  · Choose delay  \tau  via mutual information.
  · Compute cross‑map skill for both directions using increasing library sizes (e.g., 50%, 60%, …, 100% of data).
  · Test convergence by fitting a logarithmic curve to the library size vs. skill plot.
· Vagal Brake Index:
  VBI = \frac{\overline{P_{HRV}(0.1\,\text{Hz})}}{\overline{P_{fNIRS}(0.1\,\text{Hz})}} \cdot \Phi,
  where \overline{P_{HRV}} and \overline{P_{fNIRS}} are the average wavelet powers in the 0.1 Hz band during the induction phase, and \Phi is the mean PLV over the same period.

C.2.4 Biomarker Integration Module

· Mediation Analysis:
  · Build a structural equation model using lavaan (R) or semopy (Python) with bootstrap.
  · Independent variable: condition (dummy‑coded 0.1 Hz vs. 0.2 Hz).
  · Mediators: change in VBI (post‑induction minus baseline) and AUCi for sAA and cortisol.
  · Dependent variable: MSIT interference cost (reaction time difference between interference and control trials).
  · Report indirect effects with 95% bias‑corrected bootstrap CI.

